As you may have noticed, Epita's computers rarely resemble your home setup.
What you'll use to manage which application you want to open and show on screen is called a window manager, because it will help you manage the windows that are opened.
We will see how to use i3 (the window manager used on Epita's computers).
A good thing to know is that you'll need your keyboard to open apps. Actually, with i3, everything can be controlled using only your keyboard!
You will need to learn a few shortcuts to use the required apps for your practicals. Take a look at the Guidebook EPITA to have a more detailed explanation on i3.

One of the primary tools you'll use is the terminal. Open it by pressing Mod+Enter

Information
Mod is a key that has been configured at the first start of your session. It can be either the Windows key or the Alt key.
If you can't recall which one you chose, try Windows+Enter and Alt+Enter to see which one opens a window.

You can try to open new windows (like terminal) to observe the magic of i3.

You will also notice that the focus of the screen move along with the mouse pointer. So for example to write something in the terminal, you just have to move your mouse above the terminal.

In fact Bash is the language of your terminal. It allows you to interact with your computer by typing commands.

What do you use to create files?

BASH!

What do you use to delete files?
BASH!

What do you use to copy files?
BASH!

Ect... Ect... You get the idea. Bash is your new best friend.

You can check your current location in the filesystem using the pwd command in a terminal.
The location, also called path, is always given starting from the root of your computer's drive. On Linux, it's /.

Let's look at an example. If you type pwd in your terminal right now, here is what the command looks like:

Shell example(s)
$ pwd
/home/firstname.lastname/

Warning(s)
The path and the the shell commands are case-sensitive. This means that home is not the same as Home. It also means that pwd is not the same as PWD.

If you want to access your current position, starting from the root of the drive, you need to navigate through home and then firstname.lastname.

Information
On any Linux computer, the home directory is the one containing all of the current user's files.

If you ever have doubts about the usage of a command, you can use another useful command called man.

It allows you to peek into the manual of a given command. Here is an example:

Shell example(s)
$ man pwd
PWD(1)                   User Commands                    PWD(1)

NAME
pwd - print name of current/working directory

SYNOPSIS
pwd [OPTION]...
  
DESCRIPTION
Print the full filename of the current working directory.
...

Use the ls command to see your directory's contents. It lists all the files and other directories. Here is an example:

Shell example(s)
$ ls
afs example.txt

You can also show more details by adding options to the command.

Information
An option is a bit of additional information written after the command. They're usually preceded by one dash (-) for single-letter options and two dashes (--) for multi-letter options.
One specific option that is common to almost every command is the --help option. It will show you some help on how to use the command.

By using the -a option, the ls command will also display hidden files, whose names will always start with a dot.

Shell example(s)
$ ls -a
. .. afs example.txt .hidden_file

Information
If you type the command in your terminal, you can notice that 2 other directories showed up: . and ..

The . directory represents the current directory, therefore all files listed by ls are also in the . directory.
The .. directory represents the parent directory, in other words the directory containing the one we are currently in.

Here is a diagram to illustrate the example given in the output above:



Now that you can list everything you can access and see where you are, it's time to move around a bit!
To do that, simply type cd followed by the name of the directory you want to enter. Here is an example:

Shell example(s)
cd directory/

Hint(s)
As was said earlier, if you have doubts about the usage of a command, use man command to peek into its manual.

Note that we can move through multiple directories at once giving a path to the new directory.

Shell example(s)
$ cd directory1/              -> go in directory1
$ cd directory2/              -> go in directory2
$ cd ../../                   -> go in the parent of the parent directory
$ cd ./directory1/directory2/ -> go in directory2, contained in directory1, contained in current directory

Here is a diagram illustrating the example given in the shell above. Try guessing on the directory you end up after each command.



If you type ls when you first open a terminal, you may notice the presence of a directory called afs.
Enter that directory before continuing.

When you type pwd after entering this new directory, you can see that the path has changed. That's because the path of the current directory (.) changes to match the directory we entered.

Information
Just like the current directory, the parent directory also changes as you navigate through directories. It will always represent the directory of the level right above the current directory in the diagram.

Warning(s)
Always store your files in the afs when working!
Its content persists across logins on different computers.
Everything outside that special directory will be deleted upon logout!

Hint(s)
To clear your terminal, you can use the clear command.

Vim is a text editor based on keyboard shortcuts. It's a bit more complex than Emacs, but it's also really powerful.
One advantage of Vim is that it's directly available in the terminal, so you don't need to open a new window to use it.

Let's see how to use it!

Vim has three modes: normal, insert, and visual.

Normal mode
This is the default mode (when your start vim, you basically appear on this mode). In this mode, you can move the cursor, copy, paste, delete text, etc. To come back to this mode, you can press Esc (from any other mode).

Insert mode
This mode is used to insert text. To enter this mode, you need to press i (for insert) or a (for append). In this mode, you can type text as you would in any other text editor.

Visual mode
This mode is used to select text. To enter this mode, you need to press v (from the normal mode). You can then move the cursor to select text. Once you've selected the text, you can copy, paste, delete, etc.

As you may have guessed, to enter Vim, you just have to use vim keyword in your terminal.

Shell example(s)
$ vim # open vim
$ vim [PATH] # open a file with vim

Here are some useful commands to use in Vim. Don't worry, you won't have to learn them for now, you don't even have to read all of them, just know that Vim has shortcuts for EVERYTHING.

Switching modes
Towards insert mode:
  • i to insert text before the cursor
  • a to insert text after the cursor
  • o to insert text on a new line below the cursor
  • O to insert text on a new line above the cursor
Towards normal mode:
  • Esc to go back to normal mode
Towards visual mode:
  • v to select text
  • V to select lines

Moving around
  • h to move left
  • j to move down
  • k to move up
  • l to move right

Editing text
  • x to delete the character under the cursor
  • dd to delete the line under the cursor
  • yy to copy the line under the cursor
  • p to paste the copied text

Exiting vim
  • :w to save the file
  • :q to quit Vim
  • :wq to save and quit Vim
  • :q! to quit Vim without saving

Hint(s)
You can find more information on Vim by typing :help in Vim or visiting the online doc.

And actually it's the same formula for the two problems: mv.

Shell example(s)
$ mv [PREVIOUS_PATH] [NEW_PATH]

# RENAMING
$ mv wrong_filename correct_filename # renaming a file
$ mv dir1/wrong_filename2 dir1/correct_filename2 # renaming a file within a directory
$ mv dir1 dir2 # renaming a directory

# MOVING
$ mv file1.txt /new_directory/file1 # moving a file to a different directory
$ mv file1.txt /new_directory/new_file1.txt # moving and renaming a file
$ mv dir1 /new_directory/dir1 # moving a directory

So is mv handling two features: Renaming and Moving? Actually for bash, it's the same thing, one only feature. Let's explain!
When you use the mv command, you are telling the system to take an item from one path (location) and place it in another path. However, filename is contained in the path, so when you rename a file you just change its path.

Using git


To submit your work on your machine, you need to create what we call an SSH key. This key will allow us to identify you and ensure that nobody else can submit code for you.

To register one, go to your personal page on cri.epita.fr. Click on the button SSH keys on the left side of the screen. At the bottom of the page, there is a help button. Click on it and follow the instructions to add a new SSH key.

Warning(s)
This SSH key lets you submit and retrieve work on school computers, but not your personal machine: You'll need to follow the same steps on your personal computer in order to work from home.

Ok, now that you have your SSH key, you can start using Git. But what is Git? Git is the most useful tool you will use during your time at EPITA. It allows you to save your work, share it with others, and collaborate on projects. It will be the tool you use to submit your work at EPITA.

But in concrete terms, what is it? Git is a version control system. It allows you to save your work at different stages, compare different versions, and go back to a previous version if needed. Each project on git will be stored in a repository. A repository is a folder that contains all the files of your project, as well as the history of all the changes made to those files beetween the different commits.

So when you use git, you store your work in a repository. And each time you want to make changes, instead of deleting the old version and replacing it with the new one, you create a new version of your work, a new commit. This way, you can always go back to a previous version if needed.

So you have everything to gain by using Git and committing your code regularly. It allows you :
  1. to keep a constant trace of your code on the Git server, which is very useful if you lose your local version for any reason, which is stored on your computer, or when you simply want to access your code from another computer.
  2. to have a history of your code, which can be useful if you want to go back to a previous version of your code (because your last version is broken for example).

Hint(s)
If you want to remember only one thing of these explanations, commit your code regularly. (You'll see how to do it in few steps)

As previously explained, like any other directory, there are two special directories: . and ...
But here you should see a third element, a .git directory. This directory is the heart of your repository. It contains all the information about your repository, including the history of all the changes you've made to your code.
You will never have to touch this directory. It's Git's job to manage it.

Ok, now that you have your repository, it may be a good idea to move the GaulishVillage directory you created earlier into it.

Hint(s)

Warning(s)
Any file or directory outside of the repository will not be submitted. Make sure to have all your work into the repository before submitting it.

Sometimes running your code or opening your text editor can create unnecessary files (called trash files). Or sometimes you just don't want to share with others some files.
To avoid adding these files by mistake to your repository, you can write a .gitignore.

This .gitignore is a file containing the names of all the directories and files that need to be ignored by git.

Hint(s)
You can see an example of a .gitignore in the Guidelines at the start of each practical (not this one).

Here is an example of a .gitignore file:

Shell example(s)
# Ignore all files with the extension .o
*.o

# Ignore the directory named private_directory
private_directory/

# Ignore the file named trash_file
trash_file

In this tutorial, the .gitignore you will use will contain the following:

Shell example(s)
village_square/
all_potion
error_potion
perfect_potion
pipe_potion

Warning(s)
Be careful to create the .gitignore before your first commit!
You will be penalized if trash files are present in your repository or if the .gitignore is missing.

Ok, now that you have your repository and your .gitignore, it's time to commit your work. To do so, you need to three different steps.

First step: Add the files you want to commit to the staging area.
The staging area is a temporary space where you can prepare your commit. You can add files to the staging area using the git add command.

Shell example(s)
# add file1 to the staging area
$ git add file1

# add file1, file2 and file3 to the staging area
$ git add file1 file2 file3

# add all the files in the current directory and its subdirectories to the staging area
$ git add .

# same as the previous command but register the deletion of files too (what git add . doesn't do)
$ git add -A

Second step: Create a commit. A commit is a version of your work at a specific moment. You can create a commit using the git commit command.

Shell example(s)
# create a commit with the message "This is my first commit"
$ git commit -m "This is my first commit"

Warning(s)
Always write a message when you commit your work. It will help you understand what you did at that moment (and it's mandatory).

Third step: Push your commit to the git server. To do so, you need to use the git push command.

Shell example(s)
# push your commit to the git server
$ git push

Your work on each practical is tested automatically by what is called the moulinette. To do so, on top of pushing your committed work, you need to tag your commits.
A tag is like a bookmark. It allows the moulinette to understand that it needs to test your work using a specific version of your code.

To do so, you need to use the git tag -ma <name_of_the_tag> command then, push your tag like you would push your commits.
See an example below.

Shell example(s)
$ git tag -ma submit-first-submit
$ git push --follow-tags
Total 0 (delta 0), reused 0 (delta 0), pack-reused 0
To intra.forge.epita.fr:epita-prepa-acdc-prog-101-p-00-2029-firstname.lastname
* [new tag]         submit-first-submit -> submit-first-submit

Information
The git tag -ma command will add a tag to your last commit. Make sure to commit your work before tagging to ensure the last version of your work is tested.

Information
The git push command will only push your commits, not your tags. Make sure to use git push --follow-tags to push commits and tags all in one command.

There are 3 types of tags and each of them has a specific syntax that must be followed.

  • submit tags are used to submit your code for grading. This will run all the tests written for the practical. Each of them must start with submit-.
  • archi tags are used to check if your project follows the correct architecture. It will test if files are missing and if all functions return the correct type of value. Each of them starts with archi-.
  • reload tags are used during reload weeks. Those weeks right after exams allow you to redo some of the past practicals. Each of them must start with reload-.

In this practical, we'll only use submit tags.

Hint(s)
All of the allowed tags are in the Information section of the Guidelines.

Try to tag your work and push it. You will see the result generated by the moulinette on the intranet (see the link under Information in the guidelines).
If you don't see the result or you have any questions, please ask your ACDCs.

Danger(s)
This step is very important. Without it, we won't be able to test your code!
The results of those tests are also the ones that determine your grade.

Warning(s)
Note that only submit tags and reload tags can give you a grade. archi tags are only here to help you check if your code respects the and if it compiles.

Hint(s)
It's not because only commit with tags will be graded that you can't commit without tags. I really encourage you to commit regularly. It will help you to always have a backup of your work. And you can tag your work when you're ready to submit it.

Warning(s)
Only the latest tag will be taken into account for the grade.

No tags no report, no report no grade, no grade... no grade !

Before tagging your work, you should check a few things to make sure everything is correct.

  • Make sure you repository architecture respect the one given in the guidelines.
  • Make sure your .gitignore is present and correct (a sample .gitignore is always in your guidelines).
  • Make sure your code compile.
  • Make sure to test your code yourself.
  • Make sure to use one of the allowed tags.

Warning(s)
Submitted your work to the "moulinette" should not replace your own tests. It's important to test your code yourself to make sure it works as expected. Especially since the number of tags you are allowed to use will decrease more and more over the course of the year.

Are you done? Ok! Let's go!

As explained in the documentation, the grep command is used to search for a specific pattern in a file. It's a very useful tool when you want to find a specific line in a file or when you want to find all the lines that contain a specific word.

Here's how to use it:

Shell example(s)
$ grep [OPTION...] PATTERNS [FILE...]

# examples
$ grep magic file1 # search for the occurrence of "magic" in file1 and display the lines containing it

$ grep potion file1 file2 file3 # search for the occurrence of "potion" in file1, file2 and file3 and display the lines containing it

As you surely have seen displaying the documentation, the grep command has a lot of options. Don't read all of them, you just need to know they are explained in the documentation.

Let's see this:

Shell example(s)
$ man grep
GREP(1)                             User Commands                            GREP(1)

NAME
       grep, egrep, fgrep, rgrep - print lines that match patterns

SYNOPSIS
       grep [OPTION...] PATTERNS [FILE...]
       grep [OPTION...] -e PATTERNS ... [FILE...]
       grep [OPTION...] -f PATTERN_FILE ... [FILE...]

DESCRIPTION
       grep  searches  for  PATTERNS in each FILE.  PATTERNS is one or more patterns
       separated by newline characters, and grep prints each  line  that  matches  a
       pattern.   Typically  PATTERNS  should be quoted when grep is used in a shell
       command.

       A FILE of “-” stands for standard input.  If  no  FILE  is  given,  recursive
       searches  examine  the  working  directory,  and  nonrecursive  searches read
       standard input.

       In addition, the variant programs egrep, fgrep and  rgrep  are  the  same  as
       grep -E,  grep -F, and grep -r, respectively.  These variants are deprecated,
       but are provided for backward compatibility.

OPTIONS
   Generic Program Information
       --help Output a usage message and exit.

       -V, --version
              Output the version number of grep and exit.

   Pattern Syntax
       -E, --extended-regexp
              Interpret PATTERNS as extended regular expressions (EREs, see below).

       -F, --fixed-strings
              Interpret PATTERNS as fixed strings, not regular expressions.

       -G, --basic-regexp
              Interpret PATTERNS as basic regular  expressions  (BREs,  see  below).
              This is the default.

       -P, --perl-regexp
              Interpret  I<PATTERNS> as Perl-compatible regular expressions (PCREs).
              This option is experimental when combined with  the  -z  (--null-data)
              option, and grep -P may warn of unimplemented features.

   Matching Control
   [...]

Magic spells are more than just words


As you may have notice by using these spells, they need some ingredients and sometimes display a result. In the Gaulish school, we call these ingredients input and the result output. Let's see how to use them.

An input is basically everything that is given to a program. For example, the input of the cat command can be the file passed in argument.
There are a lot of possible inputs to a program, like keyboard, mouse, webcam, mic, etc.
For terminal commands, the standard input and the arguments are the main inputs of the commands.

Shell example(s)
ls /tmp

Information
/tmp is a special folder of linux systems that is wiped when the computer is shut down.

An output is basically everything that goes out of a program. For example, the output of cat file is the content of file.
There are a lot of possible outputs for a program, like text in standard or error output, images on the screen, sounds, etc.
For terminal commands, it's mainly text through standard and error outputs.

Shell example(s)
ls -a ../house1

A lot of commands write things in the terminal. There are two ways to write things:
  1. using the standard output
  2. using the standard error

Those two streams are like books. If the program wants to write an error, it will be written in the error book. Otherwise, it will be written in the output book.Everything the program writes in those books (the streams), will be displayed on the terminal by default.However, it is possible to ask the terminal to write it in files instead of printing it on the screen!

To do so, you can use the > symbol like that:

Shell example(s)
$ pwd > output_file

This is some of the possibly redirections:
  • > to redirect the standard output (and overwrite the destination file)
  • >> to redirect the standard output (and append the destination file)
  • 2> to redirect the standard error (and overwrite the destination file)
  • 2>> to redirect the standard error (and append the destination file)
  • &> to redirect both the standard output and the standard error (and overwrite the destination file)
  • &>> to redirect both the standard output and the standard error (and append the destination file)


Information
If the destination file doesn't exist, it will be created.

commands but use output redirection like above). You will have to append all potion in alphabetic order. Do not add any other characters.

You can also use the output of a command as the input of another one.
To do so, you use the | symbol, like that:

Shell example(s)
$ cat a_file
Hi there,
It is
Me

$ cat a_file | grep "e" # display only the lines containing "e"
Hi there,
Me

State of your repository


Getafix must now your provides the last versions of the receipt of the potions or be able to see all versions of the receipt that have existed. To do so, he will teach you some commands.

First we will learn to use the git status command. This command is used to display the status of the repository. To better understand it, let's execute it. But before, let's see what it does. But first, it's necessary to push your work to the git server (add-commit-push).

Shell example(s)
$ git status
On branch main
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'.

nothing to commit, working tree clean

Here you can see that you're on the last version (commit) of you repository as "Your branch is up to date with 'origin/main'" tells you.

But when you have made some modifications that are not committed yet, you'll see something different. Let's see an example. For that run these commands (you'll understand why later):

Shell example(s)
$ echo "Override" > menhir_workshop/asterix
$ touch intruderA intruderB
$ rm menhir_workshop/obelix
$ git add intruderA

$ git status
[...] # watch the result on your terminal

Information
The echo command is used to display lines of text or content of variables.

Danger(s)
Don't commit the changes you've made in this section. We'll remove them in the next section.

When you git status this time, you can see three different sections:
  • Changes to be committed: it shows the files that have been added to the staging area and that will be committed. Here, intruderA is in this section.
  • Changes not staged for commit: it shows the files that have been modified (or deleted) but not added to the staging area. Here, menhir_workshop/asterix and menhir_workshop/obelix are in this section.
  • Untracked files: it shows the files that are not tracked by git. Here, intruderB is in this section.

Please redirect the output of the git status command into library/restore_potion file, it will help Getafix to check your work.

Hint(s)
When your local repository is not up to date with the git server (you aren't on the last commit), you can use the git pull command to update it. Remember it, you may use it more than once during your studies at the Gaulish school.

We don't want to keep the changes we've made in the last section. To do so, we will use the git restore command, which as implied with the name restore the files passed in argument.
In other words, if you have modified a file, but not committed the change yet, you can remove all the changes and restore it to its last committed state.

Now Getafix want you to:

Hint(s)
To remove a file already added to the staging area, you can simply use the git rm -f command.

Once you've done that, you can check the status of your repository to see if everything is back to normal (except of course for the restore_potion file you want to keep).

Shell example(s)

Git Branches


Ok now is the time to start learning the last concept of this tutorial: branches. But what's a branch?

Imagine being on a project and you want to add a new feature. You could add it directly to the main code, but what if it doesn't work? You will have to remove all the changes you've made. And what if you want to work on two different features at the same time? You can't do that on the main code. That's where branches come in!

A branch is like a copy of the main code. You can work on it without affecting the main code. And when you're done, you can merge it back into the main code. And if it doesn't work, you can simply delete the branch.

By the way, the main code is also a branch, the main branch.

But the benefits of branch don't stop there. For example, branch can also be used to:
  • Collaborate: you can work on the same project with other people without affecting their work.
  • Be more organised: you can work on different features at the same time without mixing them and have a branch for each feature

Let's see how to use them in Git.

To create a branch, you need to use the git branch command.

Shell example(s)
$ git branch new_branch

To display it as well as all the branches, you can use the git branch command too. Pretty simple to memorize, right? Let's see the result of the command.

Shell example(s)
$ git branch
* main
sample_branch

Information
You see the * symbol before the main branch. It indicates the branch you're currently on (here main).

Once you've created a branch, you need to switch to it. To do so, you need to use the git checkout command.

Shell example(s)
$ git checkout sample_branch

Once you've finished your work on the branch, you will want to merge it back into the main branch. To do so, you need to use the git merge command.

Shell example(s)
# this command merge the selected branch into the current branch
$ git merge sample_branch

But remember what if the branch is a total failure? You can simply delete it. To do so, you need to use the git branch -d command.

Shell example(s)
$ git branch -d sample_branch

Warning(s)
You will be only graded on the main branch, so make to submit your work on it. (Except on this practical where it's explicitly asked, but the grade will be on the main branch anyway).

Warning(s)
Before making any further changes, make sure to be up to date with the git server. If you don't, push your work.

Now that you know how to create, switch, merge and delete branches, let's see how to use them in a practical case.

First Getafix ask you to:
  • Create a new branch named new_potion
  • Check it has been created
  • Switch to this branch
  • Create and add a file named rotten_potion in library with "This potion is rotten :(" inside
  • Commit and push your changes
  • Switch back to the main branch
  • Check the rotten_potion file is not in the main branch

Warning(s)
if you forget to commit your work on the branch before switching to another one, your changes will follow you. So make sure to commit your work before switching to another branch.

Hint(s)
To push a branch to the git server for the first time, you need to use the git push --set-upstream origin [BRANCH_NAME] command.

Once you've done that, Getafix ask you to do a second task:
  • Create a new branch named new_potion2
  • Switch to this branch
  • Create and add a file named perfect_potion in library with "This potion is perfect :)" inside
  • Redirect the output of the git status command into library/branch_potion file
  • Commit and push your changes
  • Switch back to the main branch
  • Check the perfect_potion file is not in the main branch
  • Merge the new_potion2 into the main branch
  • Check the perfect_potion file is now in the main branch
  • Check the branch has been deleted

After all that, redirect the output of git branch into library/branch_list file.

Hint(s)
Instead of using the git branch new_branch and git checkout new_branch commands, you can use the git checkout -b new_branch command to create and switch to a branch in one command.

Warning(s)
